If your project has many .class files:

Main.class
User.class
Order.class
Product.class

You package them together into a single JAR:

app.jar

A JAR is essentially a ZIP archive that contains:

• .class files
• Configuration files
• Resources (images, properties, etc.)
• Metadata

mvn clean

Deletes the previous build output (usually the target/ directory).

Before:

project/
├── src/
├── pom.xml
└── target/
    ├── app.jar
    └── Main.class

After:

project/
├── src/
└── pom.xml

Maven:

1. Reads your .java files.
2. Compiles them into .class files.                 -- compile      (.java → .class)
3. Runs tests (unless skipped).                     -- test         (Run unit tests)
4. Packages the compiled files into a .jar.         -- package      (.class → .jar)
